The paper proposes a statistical framework that combines probabilistic generative models and neural networks to model and forecast female reproductive hormonal patterns. This involves learning complex temporal mappings and accommodating pragmatic and minimally invasive measurement settings. The paper's focus on machine learning techniques and their application to a specific domain suggests that it is most likely to belong to the categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
